The terrain innedintely underneath consisted of small rice paddy fields
surrounded by dykes. I considered it extremely hazardous to attempt a
landing on land, due to these dykes, so headed for a river a short distance
to y right.
I shut off the engines, cut the motor witches, and disconnected the
battery, and glided into a landing on the water.
During this time the plane
was being struck by machine-gun bullets.
The plane was lended safely near the right-hund side of the river.
By
the time the water cleared from the windshield, however, the eurrent had caught
the plane and swept it into the niddle of the current.
I first ascertained that everyone in the plane wes unhurt.
I instruct-
ed that the outaide cabin door not be opened, but the stemurd had already opened
1t as the water level was approximtoly two feet below the lower part of the
door. I instructed the radio oporator to notify all concerned that everyone
was safe.
As soon as the plane stopped, the pursuit planes started machine-gunning
us. I raised the emergency hatch cover in the front of the control room and
looked up in the direction from which we were being attached. At this time
I could see the attacking planes clearly and positively identified them as
They were pontoon bi-planes. Although I eould see the markings
clenrly, I did not take time to notice whether they were mingle-place or
two-place.
The only sampans on the river were being rowed away by their occupents
rapidly. I then noticed a samplan tied up to shore directly oppoaite our
position. I turned to the radio op rator and co-pilot and told then to
instruct the passengers who could swim to jump, and that I was going to attempt
to reach shore and secure the sempen.
With this I Jumped into the water
nd started swimming toward shore.
